




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Default and the Maturity Structure in Sovereign Bonds
AU  - Arellano, Cristina
AU  - Ramanarayanan, Ananth
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/666589
DO  - 10.1086/666589
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 187
EP  - 232
VL  - 120
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper studies the maturity composition and the term structure of interest rate spreads of government debt in emerging markets. In the data, when interest rate spreads rise, debt maturity shortens and the spread on short-term bonds rises more than the spread on long-term bonds. We build a dynamic model of international borrowing with endogenous default and multiple debt maturities. Long-term debt provides a hedge against future fluctuations in spreads, whereas short-term debt is more effective at providing incentives to repay. The trade-off between these hedging and incentive benefits is quantitatively important for understanding the maturity structure in emerging markets.
AB  - This paper studies the maturity composition and the term structure of interest rate spreads of government debt in emerging markets. In the data, when interest rate spreads rise, debt maturity shortens and the spread on short-term bonds rises more than the spread on long-term bonds. We build a dynamic model of international borrowing with endogenous default and multiple debt maturities. Long-term debt provides a hedge against future fluctuations in spreads, whereas short-term debt is more effective at providing incentives to repay. The trade-off between these hedging and incentive benefits is quantitatively important for understanding the maturity structure in emerging markets.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/666589
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/666589
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Aggregate Demand for Treasury Debt
AU  - Krishnamurthy, Arvind
AU  - Vissing-Jorgensen, Annette
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/666526
DO  - 10.1086/666526
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 233
EP  - 267
VL  - 120
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Investors value the liquidity and safety of US Treasuries. We document this by showing that changes in Treasury supply have large effects on a variety of yield spreads. As a result, Treasury yields are reduced by 73 basis points, on average, from 1926 to 2008. Both the liquidity and safety attributes of Treasuries are driving this phenomenon. We document this by analyzing the spread between assets with different liquidity (but similar safety) and those with different safety (but similar liquidity). The low yield on Treasuries due to their extreme safety and liquidity suggests that Treasuries in important respects are similar to money.
AB  - Investors value the liquidity and safety of US Treasuries. We document this by showing that changes in Treasury supply have large effects on a variety of yield spreads. As a result, Treasury yields are reduced by 73 basis points, on average, from 1926 to 2008. Both the liquidity and safety attributes of Treasuries are driving this phenomenon. We document this by analyzing the spread between assets with different liquidity (but similar safety) and those with different safety (but similar liquidity). The low yield on Treasuries due to their extreme safety and liquidity suggests that Treasuries in important respects are similar to money.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/666526
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/666526
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Rich Dad, Smart Dad: Decomposing the Intergenerational Transmission of Income
AU  - Lefgren, Lars
AU  - Lindquist, Matthew J.
AU  - Sims, David
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/666590
DO  - 10.1086/666590
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 268
EP  - 303
VL  - 120
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We construct a simple model, consistent with Becker and Tomes, that decomposes the intergenerational income elasticity into the causal effect of financial resources, the mechanistic transmission of human capital, and the role that human capital plays in the determination of fathers? permanent incomes. We show how a particular set of instrumental variables could separately identify the money and human capital transmission effects. Using data from a 35 percent sample of Swedish sons and their fathers, we show that only a minority of the intergenerational income elasticity can be plausibly attributed to the causal effect of fathers? financial resources.
AB  - We construct a simple model, consistent with Becker and Tomes, that decomposes the intergenerational income elasticity into the causal effect of financial resources, the mechanistic transmission of human capital, and the role that human capital plays in the determination of fathers? permanent incomes. We show how a particular set of instrumental variables could separately identify the money and human capital transmission effects. Using data from a 35 percent sample of Swedish sons and their fathers, we show that only a minority of the intergenerational income elasticity can be plausibly attributed to the causal effect of fathers? financial resources.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/666590
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/666590
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Endogenous Entry, Product Variety, and Business Cycles
AU  - Bilbiie, Florin O.
AU  - Ghironi, Fabio
AU  - Melitz, Marc J.
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/665825
DO  - 10.1086/665825
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 304
EP  - 345
VL  - 120
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper builds a framework for the analysis of macroeconomic fluctuations that incorporates the endogenous determination of the number of producers and products over the business cycle. Economic expansions induce higher entry rates by prospective entrants subject to sunk investment costs. The sluggish response of the number of producers generates a new and potentially important endogenous propagation mechanism for business cycle models. The return to investment determines household saving decisions, producer entry, and the allocation of labor across sectors. Our framework replicates several features of business cycles and predicts procyclical profits even for preference specifications that imply countercyclical markups.
AB  - This paper builds a framework for the analysis of macroeconomic fluctuations that incorporates the endogenous determination of the number of producers and products over the business cycle. Economic expansions induce higher entry rates by prospective entrants subject to sunk investment costs. The sluggish response of the number of producers generates a new and potentially important endogenous propagation mechanism for business cycle models. The return to investment determines household saving decisions, producer entry, and the allocation of labor across sectors. Our framework replicates several features of business cycles and predicts procyclical profits even for preference specifications that imply countercyclical markups.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/665825
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/665825
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Valuation of Long-Dated Assets
AU  - Martin, Ian
Y1  - 2012/04/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/666527
DO  - 10.1086/666527
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 346
EP  - 358
VL  - 120
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I show that the pricing of a broad class of long-dated assets is driven by the possibility of extraordinarily bad news. This result does not depend on any assumptions about the existence of disasters, nor does it apply only to assets that hedge bad outcomes; indeed, it applies even to long-dated claims on the market in a lognormal world if the market?s Sharpe ratio is higher than its volatility, as appears to be the case in practice.
AB  - I show that the pricing of a broad class of long-dated assets is driven by the possibility of extraordinarily bad news. This result does not depend on any assumptions about the existence of disasters, nor does it apply only to assets that hedge bad outcomes; indeed, it applies even to long-dated claims on the market in a lognormal world if the market?s Sharpe ratio is higher than its volatility, as appears to be the case in practice.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/666527
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/666527
Y2  - 2024/03/20
